==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*ūwwalōn'', originally a diminutive of ''*ūwwōn'' ‘owl’ (Old High German ''[[huwo|hūwo]]'', Old Saxon ''[[huo|hūo]]''), probably a word imitative of the animal's call.  Cognate with Middle Low German ''ūle'' (Dutch ''[[uil]]''), Old Norse ''[[ugla]]''.  A Germanic variant ''*ūwwilōn'' was the source of Old High German ''[[uwila|ūwila]]'' (German ''[[Eule]]'').

